title: For Sale/Trade:  Custom Saiga 12
postcontent:
*** This is last bump... I am opening this up to cash purchase as there is an item on here I want, and the guy doesn't want trades.....that being said... this is last bump and this listing will be up until Friday 4/11 then I am locking it back up in the safe....  Must have proof of good guy and legal to own.... If you don't have a CPL or WAC card, I will require a B.O.S for my records only. ***

Converted Saiga 12g - This gun was torn down and built/ fabricated from the ground up by a local gunsmith, all parts were sand blasted and coated with Moly-Resin (a Teflon impregnated baked on coating), top of the line parts for conversion, modified for left hand charge, Ace Skeleton stock, Chaos Rail, HK Sights,  barrel shortened with Tromix brake welded in place to make it just at legal length and a steel plate welded to back of receiver to take the punishment of rapid fire, bolt and slide were polished and gas ports modded, adjustable gas plug added. Silver weld was used to fill in all the markings (not serial) so there is none of the laser etched upc symbol that was so ugly on these. Total build was well over $2500 couple years ago when Saigas were on the cheap. Comes with 2 20rnd drums and a 12rnd drum. I've only put maybe 3 drums through the gun, have video so you can see it run. Just sits in the safe collecting dust..... Not in a hurry or in need of getting rid of it, just putting it up to see if anything cool jumps out. For me to build this again would be well over $3000

Trade Value or trade + cash is $2500 to $3000... Like I said, to build it again now would be over $3000 and a lot of time finding all the parts.

***Response to the emails I have been getting.......

1) I consider asking me what the "lowest I'll take" as rude and the same as low-balling..... I did my homework...You do yours and make me a REASONABLE offer based on it..... 

2) If you are serious and wish to see the craftsmanship to prove the value, just ask and I can meet up with you, but please be realistic on a meeting place.... I am not driving all the way to Olympia or Everett just to let you look at my gun. I work and go to school, so I have very limited windows to meet up so please be patient.

3) Don't just state that you can get one for $1000... yes you can get an unmodified Saiga 12 for $1000..... add the cost of parts, labor etc... for a conversion.... then compare a standard conversion to the over 40hrs worth of labor that went into this shotgun.... To help with math we'll average it..... 40hrs * $50/hr (average gunsmith fee) = $2000 +parts, Mags and the original cost of gun....add it all up and it's well over my asking price ***

title: For Sale:  Colt 1900 .38 ACP Original & Letters Correct C&R         not 1902 1903 1905 or 1911 Unaltered John Browning
location: North carolina, North Carolina, United States
postcontent: Here is a very rare offering; Colt Model 1900. This model was the grandfather to the Model 1911, both designed by John Browning. The slide has a Patent date of April 20, 1897 & the magazine July 9, 1884. The Model 1900 seen many changes along the way, the main one being the rear sight. Early guns had a rear sight that pivoted down, acting as a transfer bar type safety. This sight was not liked by the buyers & around serial number 2200 Colt started altering the sights to a fixed rear sight. They started with guns that had not been shipped & offered a free upgrade to any customer that wanted to send theirs back. By serial number 3300 most guns shipped were altered during production, or manufactured with the new sight. This is important because the guns before serial # 3300 were refinished or at least had the sides refinished due to the alterations. This one is serial number 3363 & the Colt Factory Letter does not show this one having gone back to Colt. Only 4274 were ever made in this one is in the batch that were produced with the new style rear sight. It also has a round hammer, spur hammers were used to about serial # 2400. It is chambered in .38 ACP, has a 6” barrel & hard rubber grips

title: For Sale:  Marlin 782 .22 Magnum 22 WRM Bolt Mag Fed Rifle
postcontent: You are bidding on a Used Waffenfabrik Mauser Gewehr 98 bolt action rifle chambered in 7.92x57mm Mauser (Later re-designated 8mm Mauser). The Gewehr 98, also know as Gew 98, was used by the German military as their standard issue rifle from 1898 - 1935. It's overall action and design was the basis for later Mauser style rifles, such as it's replacement, the K98. The Gew 98 uses a controlled feed action and cock-on-closing style design to deliver the best possible reliability. It's 8mm round delivers similar stopping power to the .30-06 Springfield cartridge, and it's new 3-position safety made handling the rifle easier. One of the most distinctive features of this gun is it's unique rear sight. Late models abandoned this style design for a less bulky and easier to manufacture alternative. Like many of the Gew 98 rifles, this gun was manufactured for use by Turkey

The PSP-25 is simply a Baby Browning made in the U.S. under license from Fabrique Nationale because the FN “Le Bébé” has been banned from import into the U.S. since 1968.  It is no small thing for a company with Fabrique Nationale’s reputation for quality manufacture to license another entity to manufacture one of their products, but in the case of Precision Small Parts (PSP), now known as Precision Small Arms (PSA), quality of manufacture is not an issue. This gun simply exudes quality.  Even the low-end Traditional model is beautifully finished both inside and out.  You hold it in your hand and it “feels” right.  You work the action and you know immediately it is a well made weapon.
  Since I’m praising the gun so highly, I don’t think the PSA company will take it amiss if I quote from their brochure: “Le Bébé is a single action, semi-automatic, self-loading, blow-back mechanism manufactured of all steel alloy components. It is striker fired and utilizes a smooth faced, single stage draw bar trigger with pull weight of 5.25 lbs.  It can hold six rounds in its magazine and one chambered. Le Bébé’s barrel is 2.13 inches long, has 6 lands and grooves and is right-hand twisted with a radius of 3.54 inches.  Le Bébé is 4.11 inches long, stands 2.88 inches tall and is .88 inches thick.”  In addition, the PSA website states:  “When utilized with modern high-velocity ammunition, this pistol can achieve the effectiveness of a .380.  It should not be underestimated with regard to lethality.”*

The above stated pistol is stone mint. It is unfired and free of any rust, scuffs, dings etc.
The action is very very smooth and the finish has a very high luster, just tits. 
I am just testing the waters to see what is out there. 

I like to trade for quality pistols and or rifles.  Underfolder ak47
Am interested in rugers ,s&w wheel guns, beretta, walther
Mosin m44 . P38 . Other mouse guns, or????

postcontent:
AR-15 Upper Complete These are really nice, Function Tested, and ready to drop in to any lower and start firing... 

Upper is machined from 7075-T6 forgings that are hard coat anodized for wear and scratch resistance meeting MIL SPEC

Barrels drilled, reamed and buttoned from 4140, 4150 Chrome Moly, Chrome Moly Vanadium per MIL –B-11595E or 
416 stainless gun quality steel then stress relieved prior to contouring and chambering. 

Twist rate is 1 in 9. The barrels are chambered in the highly desireable .223 Wylde and therefore chambered for and suitable for firing either the Nato 5.56 designation or the .223 Remington commercial round. 


The head space is set and the barrel is tested for straightness using a 6” drop pin gage. 

The steel barrel assemblies are Parkerized to eliminate rusting. Bolts machined from tool steel, hardened and tempered 
to provide maximum wear characteristics then Parkerized to eliminate rusting. 

Bolt carriers machined from 8620 gun quality steel, heat treated and tempered to maximize strength and wear characteristics then Parkerized to eliminate rusting. These work great with our complete lowers...

The barrels on these are made from 4140 cold rolled steel and are rated at a barrel life of approximately 150,000 rounds. They are very top end. 

They are not chrome lined as most AR-'s are not. Chrome lining on modern rifles is typically used where there is a high probability of corrosive ammo being used such as AK type rifles chambered for foreign calibers... 

Since chrome lining may slightly affect accuracy, and since most AR-15 rifles are designed with accuracy as a benchmark, 
and since virtually all .223 / 5.56 Nato is non corrosive...most AR manufacturers do not chrome line barrels. 


* No FFL required on the uppers as they are not the serial numbered part and not considered a firearm.
